# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sequence-alignment
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] A **Gap penalty** is a method of scoring alignments of two or more sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] When aligning sequences, introducing gaps in the sequences can allow an alignment algorithm to match more terms than a gap-less alignment can.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] However, minimizing gaps in an alignment is important to create a useful alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Too many gaps can cause an alignment to become meaningless.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Gap penalties are used to adjust alignment scores based on the number and length of gaps.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The five main types of gap penalties are constant, linear, affine, convex, and profile-based.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] A global alignment performs an end-to-end alignment of the query sequence with the reference sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Ideally, this alignment technique is most suitable for closely related sequences of similar lengths.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The Needleman-Wunsch algorithm is a dynamic programming technique used to conduct global alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Essentially, the algorithm divides the problem into a set of sub-problems, then uses the results of the sub-problems to reconstruct a solution to the original query.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The use of semi-global alignment exists to find a particular match within a large sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] An example includes seeking promoters within a DNA sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Unlike global alignment, it compromises of no end gaps in one or both sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] If the end gaps are penalized in one sequence 1 but not in sequence 2, it produces an alignment that contains sequence 2 within sequence 1.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] A local sequence alignment matches a contiguous sub-section of one sequence with a contiguous sub-section of another.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The Smith-Waterman algorithm is motivated by giving scores for matches and mismatches.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Matches increase the overall score of an alignment whereas mismatches decrease the score.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] A good alignment then has a positive score and a poor alignment has a negative score.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The local algorithm finds an alignment with the highest score by considering only alignments that score positives and picking the best one from those.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The algorithm is a dynamic programming algorithm.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] When comparing proteins, one uses a similarity matrix which assigns a score to each possible residue pair.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The score should be positive for similar residues and negative for dissimilar residue pairs.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Gaps are usually penalized using a linear gap function that assigns an initial penalty for a gap opening, and an additional penalty for gap extensions, increasing the gap length.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Substitution matrices such as BLOSUM are used for sequence alignment of proteins.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] A Substitution matrix assigns a score for aligning any possible pair of residues.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] In general, different substitution matrices are tailored to detecting similarities among sequences that are diverged by differing degrees.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] A single matrix may be reasonably efficient over a relatively broad range of evolutionary change.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The BLOSUM-62 matrix is one of the best substitution matrices for detecting weak protein similarities.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] BLOSUM matrices with high numbers are designed for comparing closely related sequences, while those with low numbers are designed for comparing distant related sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] For example, BLOSUM-80 is used for alignments that are more similar in sequence, and BLOSUM-45 is used for alignments that have diverged from each other.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] For particularly long and weak alignments, the BLOSUM-45 matrix may provide the best results.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Short alignments are more easily detected using a matrix with a higher "relative entropy" than that of BLOSUM-62.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The BLOSUM series does not include any matrices with relative entropies suitable for the shortest queries.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] During DNA replication, the cellular replication machinery is prone to making two types of errors while duplicating the DNA.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] These two replication errors are insertions and deletions of single DNA bases from the DNA strand (indels).
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Indels can have severe biological consequences by causing mutations in the DNA strand that could result in the inactivation or over activation of the target protein.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] For example, if a one or two nucleotide indel occurs in a coding sequence the result will be a shift in the reading frame, or a frameshift mutation that may render the protein inactive.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The biological consequences of indels are often deleterious and are frequently associated with pathologies such as cancer.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] However, not all indels are frameshift mutations.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] If indels occur in trinucleotides, the result is an extension of the protein sequence that may also have implications on protein function.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] This is the simplest type of gap penalty: a fixed negative score is given to every gap, regardless of its length.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] This encourages the algorithm to make fewer, larger, gaps leaving larger contiguous sections.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Aligning two short DNA sequences, with '-' depicting a gap of one base pair.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] If each match was worth 1 point and the whole gap -1, the total score: 7 − 1 = 6.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Compared to the constant gap penalty, the linear gap penalty takes into account the length (L) of each insertion/deletion in the gap.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Therefore, if the penalty for each inserted/deleted element is B and the length of the gap L; the total gap penalty would be the product of the two BL.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] This method favors shorter gaps, with total score decreasing with each additional gap.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Unlike constant gap penalty, the size of the gap is considered.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] With a match with score 1 and each gap -1, the score here is (7 − 3 = 4).
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The most widely used gap penalty function is the affine gap penalty.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The affine gap penalty combines the components in both the constant and linear gap penalty, taking the form $A+B\cdot (L-1)$ .
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] This introduces new terms, A is known as the gap opening penalty, B the gap extension penalty and L the length of the gap.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Gap opening refers to the cost required to open a gap of any length, and gap extension the cost to extend the length of an existing gap by 1.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Often it is unclear as to what the values A and B should be as it differs according to purpose.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] In general, if the interest is to find closely related matches (e.g. removal of vector sequence during genome sequencing), a higher gap penalty should be used to reduce gap openings.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] On the other hand, gap penalty should be lowered when interested in finding a more distant match.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The relationship between A and B also have an effect on gap size.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] If the size of the gap is important, a small A and large B (more costly to extend a gap) is used and vice versa.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Only the ratio A/B is important, as multiplying both by the same positive constant k will increase all penalties by k : $kA+kB(L-1)=k(A+B(L-1))$ which does not change the relative penalty between different alignments.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Using the affine gap penalty requires the assigning of fixed penalty values for both opening and extending a gap.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] This can be too rigid for use in a biological context.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The logarithmic gap takes the form $G(L)=A+C\ln L$ and was proposed as studies had shown the distribution of indel sizes obey a power law.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Another proposed issue with the use of affine gaps is the favoritism of aligning sequences with shorter gaps.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Logarithmic gap penalty was invented to modify the affine gap so that long gaps are desirable.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] However, in contrast to this, it has been found that using logarithmatic models had produced poor alignments when compared to affine models.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Profile–profile alignment algorithms are powerful tools for detecting protein homology relationships with improved alignment accuracy.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Profile-profile alignments are based on the statistical indel frequency profiles from multiple sequence alignments generated by PSI-BLAST searches.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Rather than using substitution matrices to measure the similarity of amino acid pairs, profile–profile alignment methods require a profile-based scoring function to measure the similarity of profile vector pairs.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Profile-profile alignments employ gap penalty functions.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The gap information is usually used in the form of indel frequency profiles, which is more specific for the sequences to be aligned.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] ClustalW and MAFFT adopted this kind of gap penalty determination for their multiple sequence alignments.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Alignment accuracies can be improved using this model, especially for proteins with low sequence identity.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Some profile–profile alignment algorithms also run the secondary structure information as one term in their scoring functions, which improves alignment accuracy.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The use of alignment in computational biology often involves sequences of varying lengths.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] It is important to pick a model that would efficiently run at a known input size.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] The time taken to run the algorithm is known as the time complexity.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] There are a few challenges when it comes to working with gaps.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] When working with popular algorithms there seems to be little theoretical basis for the form of the gap penalty functions.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Consequently, for any alignment situation gap placement must be empirically determined.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Also, pairwise alignment gap penalties, such as the affine gap penalty, are often implemented independent of the amino acid types in the inserted or deleted fragment or at the broken ends, despite evidence that specific residue types are preferred in gap regions.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Finally, alignment of sequences implies alignment of the corresponding structures, but the relationships between structural features of gaps in proteins and their corresponding sequences are only imperfectly known.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Because of this incorporating structural information into gap penalties is difficult to do.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] Some algorithms use predicted or actual structural information to bias the placement of gaps.
[src:sequence-alignment/gap-penalty] However, only a minority of sequences have known structures, and most alignment problems involve sequences of unknown secondary and tertiary structure.
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] In computer science, **Hirschberg's algorithm**, named after its inventor, Dan Hirschberg, is a dynamic programming algorithm that finds the optimal sequence alignment between two strings.
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] Optimality is measured with the Levenshtein distance, defined to be the sum of the costs of insertions, replacements, deletions, and null actions needed to change one string into the other.
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] Hirschberg's algorithm is simply described as a more space-efficient version of the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm that uses dynamic programming.
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] Hirschberg's algorithm is commonly used in computational biology to find maximal global alignments of DNA and protein sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] Hirschberg's algorithm is a generally applicable algorithm for optimal sequence alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] BLAST and FASTA are suboptimal heuristics.
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] If X and Y are strings, where $\operatorname {length} (X)=n$ and $\operatorname {length} (Y)=m$ , the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm finds an optimal alignment in $O(nm)$ time, using $O(nm)$ space.
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] Hirschberg's algorithm is a clever modification of the Needleman–Wunsch Algorithm, which still takes $O(nm)$ time, but needs only $O(\min\{n,m\})$ space and is much faster in practice.
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] One application of the algorithm is finding sequence alignments of DNA or protein sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] It is also a space-efficient way to calculate the longest common subsequence between two sets of data such as with the common diff tool.
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] 2. if $(Z,W)=\operatorname {NW} (X,Y)$ is the optimal alignment of $(X,Y)$ , and $X=X^{l}+X^{r}$ is an arbitrary partition of X , there exists a partition $Y^{l}+Y^{r}$ of Y such that $\operatorname {NW} (X,Y)=\operatorname {NW} (X^{l},Y^{l})+\operatorname {NW} (X^{r},Y^{r})$ .
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] $X_{i}$ denotes the *i*-th character of X , where $1\leqslant i\leqslant \operatorname {length} (X)$ . $X_{i:j}$ denotes a substring of size $j-i+1$ , ranging from the *i*-th to the *j*-th character of X . $\operatorname {rev} (X)$ is the reversed version of X .
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] Let x be a character from X , and y be a character from Y .
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] We assume that $\operatorname {Del} (x)$ , $\operatorname {Ins} (y)$ and $\operatorname {Sub} (x,y)$ are well defined integer-valued functions.
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] These functions represent the cost of deleting x , inserting y , and replacing x with y , respectively.
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] Note that at any point, $\operatorname {NWScore}$ only requires the two most recent rows of the score matrix.
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] Thus, $\operatorname {NWScore}$ is implemented in $O(\min\{\operatorname {length} (X),\operatorname {length} (Y)\})$ space.
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] In the context of observation (2), assume that $X^{l}+X^{r}$ is a partition of X .
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] One starts with the top level call to $\operatorname {Hirschberg} ({\text{AGTACGCA}},{\text{TATGC}})$ , which splits the first argument in half: $X={\text{AGTA}}+{\text{CGCA}}$ .
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] The maximum (shown in bold) appears at `ymid = 2`, producing the partition $Y={\text{TA}}+{\text{TGC}}$ .
[src:sequence-alignment/hirschberg-s-algorithm] The leaves of the tree contain the optimal alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Multiple sequence alignments require more sophisticated methodologies than pairwise alignments, as they are more computationally complex.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Most multiple sequence alignment programs use heuristic methods rather than global optimization because identifying the optimal alignment between more than a few sequences of moderate length is prohibitively computationally expensive.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] However, heuristic methods generally cannot guarantee high-quality solutions and have been shown to fail to yield near-optimal solutions on benchmark test cases.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] To return from each particular sequence $S'_{i}$ to $S_{i}$ , remove all gaps.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] A general approach when calculating multiple sequence alignments is to use graphs to identify all of the different alignments.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] When finding alignments via graph, a *complete alignment* is created in a weighted graph that contains a set of vertices and a set of edges.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Each of the graph edges has a weight based on a certain heuristic that helps to score each *alignment* or subset of the original graph.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] When determining the best suited alignments for each MSA, a *trace* is usually generated.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] A trace is a set of *realized*, or corresponding and aligned, vertices that has a specific weight based on the edges that are selected between corresponding vertices.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] When choosing traces for a set of sequences it is necessary to choose a trace with a maximum weight to get the best alignment of the sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] There are various alignment methods used within multiple sequence to maximize scores and correctness of alignments.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Each is usually based on a certain heuristic with an insight into the evolutionary process.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Most try to replicate evolution to get the most realistic alignment possible to best predict relations between sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] A direct method for producing an MSA uses the dynamic programming technique to identify the globally optimal alignment solution.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] For nucleotide sequences, a similar gap penalty is used, but a much simpler substitution matrix, wherein only identical matches and mismatches are considered, is typical.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The scores in the substitution matrix may be either all positive or a mix of positive and negative in the case of a global alignment, but must be both positive and negative, in the case of a local alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] For *n* individual sequences, the naive method requires constructing the *n*-dimensional equivalent of the matrix formed in standard pairwise sequence alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The search space thus increases exponentially with increasing *n* and is also strongly dependent on sequence length.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Expressed with the big O notation commonly used to measure computational complexity, a naïve MSA takes *O(LengthNseqs)* time to produce.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] To find the global optimum for *n* sequences this way has been shown to be an NP-complete problem.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] In 1989, based on Carrillo-Lipman Algorithm, Altschul introduced a practical method that uses pairwise alignments to constrain the n-dimensional search space.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] In this approach pairwise dynamic programming alignments are performed on each pair of sequences in the query set, and only the space near the n-dimensional intersection of these alignments is searched for the n-way alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The MSA program optimizes the sum of all of the pairs of characters at each position in the alignment (the so-called *sum of pair* score) and has been implemented in a software program for constructing multiple sequence alignments.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] In 2019, Hosseininasab and van Hoeve showed that by using decision diagrams, MSA may be modeled in polynomial space complexity.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The most widely used approach to multiple sequence alignments uses a heuristic search known as progressive technique (also known as the hierarchical or tree method) developed by Da-Fei Feng and Doolittle in 1987.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Progressive alignment builds up a final MSA by combining pairwise alignments beginning with the most similar pair and progressing to the most distantly related.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The initial *guide tree* is determined by an efficient clustering method such as neighbor-joining or *unweighted pair group method with arithmetic mean* (UPGMA), and may use distances based on the number of identical two-letter sub-sequences (as in FASTA rather than a dynamic programming alignment).
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Progressive alignments are not guaranteed to be globally optimal.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The primary problem is that when errors are made at any stage in growing the MSA, these errors are then propagated through to the final result.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Performance is also particularly bad when all of the sequences in the set are rather distantly related.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Most modern progressive methods modify their scoring function with a secondary weighting function that assigns scaling factors to individual members of the query set in a nonlinear fashion based on their phylogenetic distance from their nearest neighbors.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] This corrects for non-random selection of the sequences given to the alignment program.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Progressive alignment methods are efficient enough to implement on a large scale for many (100s to 1000s) sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] A popular progressive alignment method has been the Clustal family.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] ClustalW is used extensively for phylogenetic tree construction, in spite of the author's explicit warnings that unedited alignments should not be used in such studies and as input for protein structure prediction by homology modeling.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] European Bioinformatics Institute (EMBL-EBI) announced that CLustalW2 will expire in August 2015.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] They recommend Clustal Omega which performs based on seeded guide trees and HMM profile-profile techniques for protein alignments.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] An alternative tool for progressive DNA alignments is *multiple alignment using fast Fourier transform* (MAFFT).
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Another common progressive alignment method named T-Coffee is slower than Clustal and its derivatives but generally produces more accurate alignments for distantly related sequence sets.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] T-Coffee calculates pairwise alignments by combining the direct alignment of the pair with indirect alignments that aligns each sequence of the pair to a third sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] It uses the output from Clustal as well as another local alignment program LALIGN, which finds multiple regions of local alignment between two sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The resulting alignment and phylogenetic tree are used as a guide to produce new and more accurate weighting factors.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Because progressive methods are heuristics that are not guaranteed to converge to a global optimum, alignment quality can be difficult to evaluate and their true biological significance can be obscure.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] A semi-progressive method that improves alignment quality and does not use a lossy heuristic while running in polynomial time has been implemented in the program PSAlign.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] A set of methods to produce MSAs while reducing the errors inherent in progressive methods are classified as "iterative" because they work similarly to progressive methods but repeatedly realign the initial sequences as well as adding new sequences to the growing MSA.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] One reason progressive methods are so strongly dependent on a high-quality initial alignment is the fact that these alignments are always incorporated into the final result – that is, once a sequence has been aligned into the MSA, its alignment is not considered further.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] This approximation improves efficiency at the cost of accuracy.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] By contrast, iterative methods can return to previously calculated pairwise alignments or sub-MSAs incorporating subsets of the query sequence as a means of optimizing a general objective function such as finding a high-quality alignment score.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] A variety of subtly different iteration methods have been implemented and made available in software packages; reviews and comparisons have been useful but generally refrain from choosing a "best" technique.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The software package PRRN/PRRP uses a hill-climbing algorithm to optimize its MSA alignment score and iteratively corrects both alignment weights and locally divergent or "gappy" regions of the growing MSA.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] PRRP performs best when refining an alignment previously constructed by a faster method.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Another iterative program, DIALIGN, takes an unusual approach of focusing narrowly on local alignments between sub-segments or sequence motifs without introducing a gap penalty.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The alignment of individual motifs is then achieved with a matrix representation similar to a dot-matrix plot in a pairwise alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] An alternative method that uses fast local alignments as anchor points or *seeds* for a slower global-alignment procedure is implemented in the CHAOS/DIALIGN suite.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] A third popular iteration-based method named MUSCLE (multiple sequence alignment by log-expectation) improves on progressive methods with a more accurate distance measure to assess the relatedness of two sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The distance measure is updated between iteration stages (although, in its original form, MUSCLE contained only 2-3 iterations depending on whether refinement was enabled).
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Consensus methods attempt to find the optimal multiple sequence alignment given multiple different alignments of the same set of sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] There are two commonly used consensus methods, M-COFFEE and MergeAlign.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] M-COFFEE uses multiple sequence alignments generated by seven different methods to generate consensus alignments.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] MergeAlign is capable of generating consensus alignments from any number of input alignments generated using different models of sequence evolution or different methods of multiple sequence alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The default option for MergeAlign is to infer a consensus alignment using alignments generated using 91 different models of protein sequence evolution.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] A hidden Markov model (HMM) is a probabilistic model that can assign likelihoods to all possible combinations of gaps, matches, and mismatches, to determine the most likely MSA or set of possible MSAs.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] HMMs can produce a single highest-scoring output but can also generate a family of possible alignments that can then be evaluated for biological significance.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] HMMs can produce both global and local alignments.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Although HMM-based methods have been developed relatively recently, they offer significant improvements in computational speed, especially for sequences that contain overlapping regions.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Typical HMM-based methods work by representing an MSA as a form of directed acyclic graph known as a partial-order graph, which consists of a series of nodes representing possible entries in the columns of an MSA.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] In this representation a column that is absolutely conserved (that is, that all the sequences in the MSA share a particular character at a particular position) is coded as a single node with as many outgoing connections as there are possible characters in the next column of the alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] In the terms of a typical hidden Markov model, the observed states are the individual alignment columns and the "hidden" states represent the presumed ancestral sequence from which the sequences in the query set are hypothesized to have descended.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] An efficient search variant of the dynamic programming method, named the Viterbi algorithm, is generally used to successively align the growing MSA to the next sequence in the query set to produce a new MSA.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] This is distinct from progressive alignment methods because the alignment of prior sequences is updated at each new sequence addition.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] However, like progressive methods, this technique can be influenced by the order in which the sequences in the query set are integrated into the alignment, especially when the sequences are distantly related.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Several software programs are available in which variants of HMM-based methods have been implemented and which are noted for their scalability and efficiency, although properly using an HMM method is more complex than using more common progressive methods.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The simplest is Partial-Order Alignment (POA), and a similar more general method is implemented in the Sequence Alignment and Modeling System (SAM) software package. and HMMER.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] SAM has been used as a source of alignments for protein structure prediction to participate in the Critical Assessment of Structure Prediction (CASP) structure prediction experiment and to develop a database of predicted proteins in the yeast species *S. cerevisiae*.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] HHsearch is a software package for the detection of remotely related protein sequences based on the pairwise comparison of HMMs.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] A server running HHsearch (HHpred) was the fastest of 10 automatic structure prediction servers in the CASP7 and CASP8 structure prediction competitions.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Most multiple sequence alignment methods try to minimize the number of insertions/deletions (gaps) and, as a consequence, produce compact alignments.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] This causes several problems if the sequences to be aligned contain non-homologous regions, if gaps are informative in a phylogeny analysis.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] These problems are common in newly produced sequences that are poorly annotated and may contain frame-shifts, wrong domains or non-homologous spliced exons.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The first such method was developed in 2005 by Löytynoja and Goldman.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The same authors released a software package called *PRANK* in 2008.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] PRANK improves alignments when insertions are present.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Nevertheless, it runs slowly compared to progressive and/or iterative methods which have been developed for several years.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] In 2012, two new phylogeny-aware tools appeared.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] One is called *PAGAN* that was developed by the same team as PRANK.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The other is *ProGraphMSA* developed by Szalkowski.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Both software packages were developed independently but share common features, notably the use of graph algorithms to improve the recognition of non-homologous regions, and an improvement in code making these software faster than PRANK.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Motif finding, also known as profile analysis, is a method of locating sequence motifs in global MSAs that is both a means of producing a better MSA and a means of producing a scoring matrix for use in searching other sequences for similar motifs.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The alignment can then be refined using these matrices.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] In standard profile analysis, the matrix includes entries for each possible character as well as entries for gaps.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Alternatively, statistical pattern-finding algorithms can identify motifs as a precursor to an MSA rather than as a derivation.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] In many cases when the query set contains only a small number of sequences or contains only highly related sequences, pseudocounts are added to normalize the distribution reflected in the scoring matrix.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] In particular, this corrects zero-probability entries in the matrix to values that are small but nonzero.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Blocks analysis is a method of motif finding that restricts motifs to ungapped regions in the alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Blocks can be generated from an MSA or they can be extracted from unaligned sequences using a precalculated set of common motifs previously generated from known gene families.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Block scoring generally relies on the spacing of high-frequency characters rather than on the calculation of an explicit substitution matrix.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Statistical pattern-matching has been implemented using both the expectation-maximization algorithm and the Gibbs sampler.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] One of the most common motif-finding tools, named Multiple EM for Motif Elicitation (MEME), uses expectation maximization and hidden Markov methods to generate motifs that are then used as search tools by its companion MAST in the combined suite MEME/MAST.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Non-coding DNA regions, especially transcription factor binding sites (TFBSs), are conserved, but not necessarily evolutionarily related, and may have converged from non-common ancestors.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Thus, the assumptions used to align protein sequences and DNA coding regions are inherently different from those that hold for TFBS sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Although it is meaningful to align DNA coding regions for homologous sequences using mutation operators, alignment of binding site sequences for the same transcription factor cannot rely on evolutionary related mutation operations.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Similarly, the evolutionary operator of point mutations can be used to define an edit distance for coding sequences, but this has little meaning for TFBS sequences because any sequence variation has to maintain a certain level of specificity for the binding site to function.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] This becomes specifically important when trying to align known TFBS sequences to build supervised models to predict unknown locations of the same TFBS.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Standard optimization techniques in computer science – both of which were inspired by, but do not directly reproduce, physical processes – have also been used in an attempt to more efficiently produce quality MSAs.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] One such technique, genetic algorithms, has been used for MSA production in an attempt to broadly simulate the hypothesized evolutionary process that gave rise to the divergence in the query set.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The method works by breaking a series of possible MSAs into fragments and repeatedly rearranging those fragments with the introduction of gaps at varying positions.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] A general objective function is optimized during the simulation, most generally the "sum of pairs" maximization function introduced in dynamic programming-based MSA methods.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] A technique for protein sequences has been implemented in the software program SAGA (Sequence Alignment by Genetic Algorithm) and its equivalent in RNA is called RAGA.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The technique of simulated annealing, by which an existing MSA produced by another method is refined by a series of rearrangements designed to find better regions of alignment space than the one the input alignment already occupies.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Like the genetic algorithm method, simulated annealing maximizes an objective function like the sum-of-pairs function.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] This approach has been implemented in the program MSASA (Multiple Sequence Alignment by Simulated Annealing).
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Mathematical programming and in particular mixed integer programming models are another approach to solve MSA problems.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The advantage of such optimization models is that they can be used to find the optimal MSA solution more efficiently compared to the traditional DP approach.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] This is due in part, to the applicability of decomposition techniques for mathematical programs, where the MSA model is decomposed into smaller parts and iteratively solved until the optimal solution is found.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Example algorithms used to solve mixed integer programming models of MSA include branch and price and Benders decomposition.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Although exact approaches are computationally slow compared to heuristic algorithms for MSA, they are guaranteed to reach the optimal solution eventually, even for large-size problems.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] In January 2017, D-Wave Systems announced that its qbsolv open-source quantum computing software had been successfully used to find a faster solution to the MSA problem.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The necessary use of heuristics for multiple alignment means that for an arbitrary set of proteins, there is always a good chance that an alignment will contain errors.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] For example, an evaluation of several leading alignment programs using the BAliBase benchmark found that at least 24% of all pairs of aligned amino acids were incorrectly aligned.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] These errors can arise because of unique insertions into one or more regions of sequences, or through some more complex evolutionary process leading to proteins that do not align easily by sequence alone.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] As the number of sequence and their divergence increases many more errors will be made simply because of the heuristic nature of MSA algorithms.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Multiple sequence alignment viewers enable alignments to be visually reviewed, often by inspecting the quality of alignment for annotated functional sites on two or more sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Many also enable the alignment to be edited to correct these (usually minor) errors, in order to obtain an optimal 'curated' alignment suitable for use in phylogenetic analysis or comparative modeling.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] However, as the number of sequences increases and especially in genome-wide studies that involve many MSAs it is impossible to manually curate all alignments.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Furthermore, manual curation is subjective.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] And finally, even the best expert cannot confidently align the more ambiguous cases of highly diverged sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] In such cases it is common practice to use automatic procedures to exclude unreliably aligned regions from the MSA.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] For the purpose of phylogeny reconstruction (see below) the Gblocks program is widely used to remove alignment blocks suspect of low quality, according to various cutoffs on the number of gapped sequences in alignment columns.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] However, these criteria may excessively filter out regions with insertion/deletion events that may still be aligned reliably, and these regions might be desirable for other purposes such as detection of positive selection.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] A few alignment algorithms output site-specific scores that allow the selection of high-confidence regions.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Such a service was first offered by the SOAP program, which tests the robustness of each column to perturbation in the parameters of the popular alignment program CLUSTALW.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The T-Coffee program uses a library of alignments in the construction of the final MSA, and its output MSA is colored according to confidence scores that reflect the agreement between different alignments in the library regarding each aligned residue.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Its extension, Transitive Consistency Score (TCS), uses T-Coffee libraries of pairwise alignments to evaluate any third party MSA.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Pairwise projections can be produced using fast or slow methods, thus allowing a trade-off between speed and accuracy.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Another alignment program that can output an MSA with confidence scores is FSA, which uses a statistical model that allows calculation of the uncertainty in the alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The HoT (Heads-Or-Tails) score can be used as a measure of site-specific alignment uncertainty due to the existence of multiple co-optimal solutions.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The GUIDANCE program calculates a similar site-specific confidence measure based on the robustness of the alignment to uncertainty in the guide tree that is used in progressive alignment programs.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] An alternative, more statistically justified approach to assess alignment uncertainty is the use of probabilistic evolutionary models for joint estimation of phylogeny and alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] A Bayesian approach allows calculation of posterior probabilities of estimated phylogeny and alignment, which is a measure of the confidence in these estimates.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] In this case, a posterior probability can be calculated for each site in the alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Such an approach was implemented in the program BAli-Phy.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] There are free programs available for visualization of multiple sequence alignments, for example Jalview and UGENE.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Multiple sequence alignments can be used to create a phylogenetic tree.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The first is because functional domains that are known in annotated sequences can be used for alignment in non-annotated sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] The other is that conserved regions known to be functionally important can be found.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] This makes it possible for multiple sequence alignments to be used to analyze and find evolutionary relationships through homology between sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Point mutations and insertion or deletion events (called indels) can be detected.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Multiple sequence alignments can also be used to identify functionally important sites, such as binding sites, active sites, or sites corresponding to other key functions, by locating conserved domains.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] When looking at multiple sequence alignments, it is useful to consider different aspects of the sequences when comparing sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] These aspects include identity, similarity, and homology.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Identity means that the sequences have identical residues at their respective positions.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] On the other hand, similarity has to do with the sequences being compared having similar residues quantitatively.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] For example, in terms of nucleotide sequences, pyrimidines are considered similar to each other, as are purines.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] Similarity ultimately leads to homology, in that the more similar sequences are, the closer they are to being homologous.
[src:sequence-alignment/multiple-sequence-alignment] This similarity in sequences can then go on to help find common ancestry.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The **Needleman–Wunsch algorithm** is an algorithm used in bioinformatics to align protein or nucleotide sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] It was one of the first applications of dynamic programming to compare biological sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The algorithm essentially divides a large problem (e.g. the full sequence) into a series of smaller problems, and it uses the solutions to the smaller problems to find an optimal solution to the larger problem.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] It is also sometimes referred to as the optimal matching algorithm and the global alignment technique.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The Needleman–Wunsch algorithm is still widely used for optimal global alignment, particularly when the quality of the global alignment is of the utmost importance.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The algorithm assigns a score to every possible alignment, and the purpose of the algorithm is to find all possible alignments having the highest score.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] This algorithm can be used for any two strings.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] First construct a grid such as one shown in Figure 1 above.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Start the first string in the top of the third column and start the other string at the start of the third row.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Fill out the rest of the column and row headers as in Figure 1.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] There should be no numbers in the grid yet.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Next, decide how to score each individual pair of letters.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Each of these scenarios is assigned a score and the sum of the scores of all the pairings is the score of the whole alignment candidate.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Different systems exist for assigning scores; some have been outlined in the Scoring systems section below.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Start with a zero in the first row, first column (not including the cells containing nucleotides).
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Move through the cells row by row, calculating the score for each cell.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The score is calculated by comparing the scores of the cells neighboring to the left, top or top-left (diagonal) of the cell and adding the appropriate score for match, mismatch or indel.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The resulting score for the cell is the highest of the three candidate scores.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Given there is no 'top' or 'top-left' cells for the first row only the existing cell to the left can be used to calculate the score of each cell.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Hence −1 is added for each shift to the right as this represents an indel from the previous score.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The same applies to the first column as only the existing score above each cell can be used.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The first case with existing scores in all 3 directions is the intersection of our first letters (in this case G and G).
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The cell which gave the highest candidate score must also be recorded.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] In the completed diagram in figure 1 above, this is represented as an arrow from the cell in row and column 2 to the cell in row and column 1.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] In this case, all directions reaching the highest candidate score must be noted as possible origin cells in the finished diagram in figure 1, e.g. in the cell in row and column 6.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Filling in the table in this manner gives the scores of all possible alignment candidates, the score in the cell on the bottom right represents the alignment score for the best alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Mark a path from the cell on the bottom right back to the cell on the top left by following the direction of the arrows.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The simplest scoring schemes simply give a value for each match, mismatch and indel.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The step-by-step guide above uses match = 1, mismatch = −1, indel = −1.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Thus the lower the alignment score the larger the edit distance, for this scoring system one wants a high score.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] For this system the alignment score will represent the edit distance between the two strings.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] More complicated scoring systems attribute values not only for the type of alteration, but also for the letters that are involved.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] For example, a match between A and A may be given 1, but a match between T and T may be given 4.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Here (assuming the first scoring system) more importance is given to the Ts matching than the As, i.e. the Ts matching is assumed to be more significant to the alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] This weighting based on letters also applies to mismatches.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] In order to represent all the possible combinations of letters and their resulting scores a similarity matrix is used.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Each score represents a switch from one of the letters the cell matches to the other.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Hence this represents all possible matches and mismatches (for an alphabet of ACGT).
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Note all the matches go along the diagonal, also not all the table needs to be filled, only this triangle because the scores are reciprocal.= (Score for A → C = Score for C → A).
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Different scoring matrices have been statistically constructed which give weight to different actions appropriate to a particular scenario.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Having weighted scoring matrices is particularly important in protein sequence alignment due to the varying frequency of the different amino acids.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] When aligning sequences there are often gaps (i.e. indels), sometimes large ones.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Biologically, a large gap is more likely to occur as one large deletion as opposed to multiple single deletions.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Hence two small indels should have a worse score than one large one.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The simple and common way to do this is via a large gap-start score for a new indel and a smaller gap-extension score for every letter which extends the indel.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] For example, new-indel may cost -5 and extend-indel may cost -1.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] or any alignment with a 4 long gap in preference over multiple small gaps.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Scores for aligned characters are specified by a similarity matrix.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Here, *S*(*a*, *b*) is the similarity of characters *a* and *b*.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] It uses a linear gap penalty, here called d.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] To find the alignment with the highest score, a two-dimensional array (or matrix) *F* is allocated.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The entry in row *i* and column *j* is denoted here by $F_{ij}$ .
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] There is one row for each character in sequence *A*, and one column for each character in sequence *B*.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Thus, if aligning sequences of sizes *n* and *m*, the amount of memory used is in $O(nm)$ .
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Hirschberg's algorithm only holds a subset of the array in memory and uses $\Theta (\min\{n,m\})$ space, but is otherwise similar to Needleman-Wunsch (and still requires $O(nm)$ time).
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] As the algorithm progresses, the $F_{ij}$ will be assigned to be the optimal score for the alignment of the first $i=0,\dotsc ,n$ characters in *A* and the first $j=0,\dotsc ,m$ characters in *B*.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Once the *F* matrix is computed, the entry $F_{nm}$ gives the maximum score among all possible alignments.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] To compute an alignment that actually gives this score, you start from the bottom right cell, and compare the value with the three possible sources (Match, Insert, and Delete above) to see which it came from.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] If Match, then $A_{i}$ and $B_{j}$ are aligned, if Delete, then $A_{i}$ is aligned with a gap, and if Insert, then $B_{j}$ is aligned with a gap.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Computing the score $F_{ij}$ for each cell in the table is an $O(1)$ operation.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Thus the time complexity of the algorithm for two sequences of length n and m is $O(mn)$ .
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] It has been shown that it is possible to improve the running time to $O(mn/\log n)$ using the Method of Four Russians.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The original purpose of the algorithm described by Needleman and Wunsch was to find similarities in the amino acid sequences of two proteins.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Needleman and Wunsch describe their algorithm explicitly for the case when the alignment is penalized solely by the matches and mismatches, and gaps have no penalty (*d*=0).
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The corresponding dynamic programming algorithm takes cubic time.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] A better dynamic programming algorithm with quadratic running time for the same problem (no gap penalty) was introduced later by David Sankoff in 1972.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Similar quadratic-time algorithms were discovered independently by T.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Vintsyuk in 1968 for speech processing ("time warping"), and by Robert A.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Needleman and Wunsch formulated their problem in terms of maximizing similarity.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Another possibility is to minimize the edit distance between sequences, introduced by Vladimir Levenshtein.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Sellers showed in 1974 that the two problems are equivalent.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] However, the algorithm is expensive with respect to time and space, proportional to the product of the length of two sequences and hence is not suitable for long sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Recent development has focused on improving the time and space cost of the algorithm while maintaining quality.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] For example, in 2013, a Fast Optimal Global Sequence Alignment Algorithm (FOGSAA), suggested alignment of nucleotide/protein sequences faster than other optimal global alignment methods, including the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The paper claims that when compared to the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm, FOGSAA achieves a time gain of 70–90% for highly similar nucleotide sequences (with > 80% similarity), and 54–70% for sequences having 30–80% similarity.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Stereo matching is an essential step in the process of 3D reconstruction from a pair of stereo images.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] When images have been rectified, an analogy can be drawn between aligning nucleotide and protein sequences and matching pixels belonging to scan lines, since both tasks aim at establishing optimal correspondence between two strings of characters.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Although in many applications image rectification can be performed, e.g. by camera resectioning or calibration, it is sometimes impossible or impractical since the computational cost of accurate rectification models prohibit their usage in real-time applications.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Moreover, none of these models is suitable when a camera lens displays unexpected distortions, such as those generated by raindrops, weatherproof covers or dust.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] By extending the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm, a line in the 'left' image can be associated to a curve in the 'right' image by finding the alignment with the highest score in a three-dimensional array (or matrix).
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Experiments demonstrated that such extension allows dense pixel matching between unrectified or distorted images.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] The Needleman–Wunsch algorithm has also been applied to the comparison of artificial neural network architectures.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Inspired by how global sequence alignment identifies similarities in the aforementioned biological sequences, this approach represents neural networks as sequences of computational layers or blocks.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] By aligning these sequences, architectural similarity can be quantified in a principled manner.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] This method has been successfully used in neural architecture search (NAS), particularly in approaches based on evolutionary algorithms.
[src:sequence-alignment/needleman-wunsch-algorithm] Architectural similarity can be assessed without requiring model training, enabling more efficient guidance of diversity during population-based search, preventing premature convergence.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In bioinformatics, a **sequence alignment** is a way of arranging the sequences of DNA, RNA, or protein to identify regions of similarity that may be a consequence of functional, structural, or evolutionary relationships between the sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Aligned sequences of nucleotide or amino acid residues are typically represented as rows within a matrix.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Gaps are inserted between the residues so that identical or similar characters are aligned in successive columns.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Sequence alignments are also used for non-biological sequences such as calculating the distance cost between strings in a natural language, or to display financial data.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] If two sequences in an alignment share a common ancestor, mismatches can be interpreted as point mutations and gaps as indels (that is, insertion or deletion mutations) introduced in one or both lineages in the time since they diverged from one another.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In sequence alignments of proteins, the degree of similarity between amino acids occupying a particular position in the sequence can be interpreted as a rough measure of how conserved a particular region or sequence motif is among lineages.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The absence of substitutions, or the presence of only very conservative substitutions (that is, the substitution of amino acids whose side chains have similar biochemical properties) in a particular region of the sequence, suggest that this region has structural or functional importance.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Although DNA and RNA nucleotide bases are more similar to each other than are amino acids, the conservation of base pairs can indicate a similar functional or structural role.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Very short or very similar sequences can be aligned by hand.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] However, most interesting problems require the alignment of lengthy, highly variable or extremely numerous sequences that cannot be aligned solely by human effort.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Various algorithms were devised to produce high-quality sequence alignments, and occasionally in adjusting the final results to reflect patterns that are difficult to represent algorithmically (especially in the case of nucleotide sequences).
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Computational approaches to sequence alignment generally fall into two categories: *global alignments* and *local alignments*.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Calculating a global alignment is a form of global optimization that "forces" the alignment to span the entire length of all query sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] By contrast, local alignments identify regions of similarity within long sequences that are often widely divergent overall.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Local alignments are often preferable, but can be more difficult to calculate because of the additional challenge of identifying the regions of similarity.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] A variety of computational algorithms have been applied to the sequence alignment problem.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] These include slow but formally correct methods like dynamic programming.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] These also include efficient, heuristic algorithms or probabilistic methods designed for large-scale database search, that do not guarantee to find best matches.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Alignments are commonly represented both graphically and in text format.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In almost all sequence alignment representations, sequences are written in rows arranged so that aligned residues appear in successive columns.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In text formats, aligned columns containing identical or similar characters are indicated with a system of conservation symbols.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] As in the image above, an asterisk or pipe symbol is used to show identity between two columns; other less common symbols include a colon for conservative substitutions and a period for semiconservative substitutions.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Many sequence visualization programs also use color to display information about the properties of the individual sequence elements; in DNA and RNA sequences, this equates to assigning each nucleotide its own color.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In protein alignments, such as the one in the image above, color is often used to indicate amino acid properties to aid in judging the conservation of a given amino acid substitution.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Sequence alignments can be stored in a wide variety of text-based file formats, many of which were originally developed in conjunction with a specific alignment program or implementation.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Most web-based tools allow a limited number of input and output formats, such as FASTA format and GenBank format and the output is not easily editable.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Several conversion programs that provide graphical and/or command line interfaces are available, such as READSEQ and EMBOSS.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] There are also several programming packages which provide this conversion functionality, such as BioPython, BioRuby and BioPerl.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The SAM/BAM files use the CIGAR (Compact Idiosyncratic Gapped Alignment Report) string format to represent an alignment of a sequence to a reference by encoding a sequence of events (e.g. match/mismatch, insertions, deletions).
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The original CIGAR format from the exonerate alignment program did not distinguish between mismatches or matches with the M character.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The SAMv1 spec document defines newer CIGAR codes.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In most cases it is preferred to use the '=' and 'X' characters to denote matches or mismatches rather than the older 'M' character, which is ambiguous.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Global alignments, which attempt to align every residue in every sequence, are most useful when the sequences in the query set are similar and of roughly equal size.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] (This does not mean global alignments cannot start and/or end in gaps.) A general global alignment technique is the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm, which is based on dynamic programming.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Local alignments are more useful for dissimilar sequences that are suspected to contain regions of similarity or similar sequence motifs within their larger sequence context.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The Smith–Waterman algorithm is a general local alignment method based on the same dynamic programming scheme but with additional choices to start and end at any place.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Hybrid methods, known as semi-global or "glocal" (short for **glo**bal-lo**cal**) methods, search for the best possible partial alignment of the two sequences (in other words, a combination of one or both starts and one or both ends is stated to be aligned).
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] This can be especially useful when the downstream part of one sequence overlaps with the upstream part of the other sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In this case, neither global nor local alignment is entirely appropriate: a global alignment would attempt to force the alignment to extend beyond the region of overlap, while a local alignment might not fully cover the region of overlap.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Another case where semi-global alignment is useful is when one sequence is short (for example a gene sequence) and the other is very long (for example a chromosome sequence).
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In that case, the short sequence should be globally (fully) aligned but only a local (partial) alignment is desired for the long sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Fast expansion of genetic data challenges speed of current DNA sequence alignment algorithms.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Essential needs for an efficient and accurate method for DNA variant discovery demand innovative approaches for parallel processing in real time.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Optical computing approaches have been suggested as promising alternatives to the current electrical implementations, yet their applicability remains to be tested [1].
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Pairwise sequence alignment methods are used to find the best-matching piecewise (local or global) alignments of two query sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Pairwise alignments can only be used between two sequences at a time, but they are efficient to calculate and are often used for methods that do not require extreme precision (such as searching a database for sequences with high similarity to a query).
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The three primary methods of producing pairwise alignments are dot-matrix methods, dynamic programming, and word methods; however, multiple sequence alignment techniques can also align pairs of sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Although each method has its individual strengths and weaknesses, all three pairwise methods have difficulty with highly repetitive sequences of low information content - especially where the number of repetitions differ in the two sequences to be aligned.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] One way of quantifying the utility of a given pairwise alignment is the 'maximal unique match' (MUM), or the longest subsequence that occurs in both query sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Longer MUM sequences typically reflect closer relatedness in the multiple sequence alignment of genomes in computational biology.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Identification of MUMs and other potential anchors, is the first step in larger alignment systems such as MUMmer.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Anchors are the areas between two genomes where they are highly similar.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] To understand what a MUM is we can break down each word in the acronym.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Match implies that the substring occurs in both sequences to be aligned.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Unique means that the substring occurs only once in each sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Finally, maximal states that the substring is not part of another larger string that fulfills both prior requirements.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The idea behind this, is that long sequences that match exactly and occur only once in each genome are almost certainly part of the global alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The dot-matrix approach, which implicitly produces a family of alignments for individual sequence regions, is qualitative and conceptually simple, though time-consuming to analyze on a large scale.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In the absence of noise, it can be easy to visually identify certain sequence features—such as insertions, deletions, repeats, or inverted repeats—from a dot-matrix plot.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] To construct a dot-matrix plot, the two sequences are written along the top row and leftmost column of a two-dimensional matrix and a dot is placed at any point where the characters in the appropriate columns match—this is a typical recurrence plot.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Some implementations vary the size or intensity of the dot depending on the degree of similarity of the two characters, to accommodate conservative substitutions.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The dot plots of very closely related sequences will appear as a single line along the matrix's main diagonal.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Problems with dot plots as an information display technique include: noise, lack of clarity, non-intuitiveness, difficulty extracting match summary statistics and match positions on the two sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] There is also much wasted space where the match data is inherently duplicated across the diagonal and most of the actual area of the plot is taken up by either empty space or noise, and, finally, dot-plots are limited to two sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] None of these limitations apply to Miropeats alignment diagrams but they have their own particular flaws.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Dot plots can also be used to assess repetitiveness in a single sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] A sequence can be plotted against itself and regions that share significant similarities will appear as lines off the main diagonal.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] This effect occurs when a protein consists of multiple similar structural domains.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The technique of dynamic programming can be applied to produce global alignments via the Needleman-Wunsch algorithm, and local alignments via the Smith-Waterman algorithm.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In typical usage, protein alignments use a substitution matrix to assign scores to amino-acid matches or mismatches, and a gap penalty for matching an amino acid in one sequence to a gap in the other.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] DNA and RNA alignments may use a scoring matrix, but in practice often simply assign a positive match score, a negative mismatch score, and a negative gap penalty.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] (In standard dynamic programming, the score of each amino acid position is independent of the identity of its neighbors, and therefore base stacking effects are not taken into account.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] However, it is possible to account for such effects by modifying the algorithm.) A common extension to standard linear gap costs are affine gap costs.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Here two different gap penalties are applied for opening a gap and for extending a gap.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Typically the former is much larger than the latter, e.g. -10 for gap open and -2 for gap extension.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] This results in fewer gaps in an alignment and residues and gaps are kept together, traits more representative of biological sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The Gotoh algorithm implements affine gap costs by using three matrices.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Dynamic programming can be useful in aligning nucleotide to protein sequences, a task complicated by the need to take into account frameshift mutations (usually insertions or deletions).
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The framesearch method produces a series of global or local pairwise alignments between a query nucleotide sequence and a search set of protein sequences, or vice versa.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Its ability to evaluate frameshifts offset by an arbitrary number of nucleotides makes the method useful for sequences containing large numbers of indels, which can be very difficult to align with more efficient heuristic methods.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In practice, the method requires large amounts of computing power or a system whose architecture is specialized for dynamic programming.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The BLAST and EMBOSS suites provide basic tools for creating translated alignments (though some of these approaches take advantage of side-effects of sequence searching capabilities of the tools).
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] More general methods are available from open-source software such as GeneWise.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The dynamic programming method is guaranteed to find an optimal alignment given a particular scoring function; however, identifying a good scoring function is often an empirical rather than a theoretical matter.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Although dynamic programming is extensible to more than two sequences, it is prohibitively slow for large numbers of sequences or extremely long sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Word methods, also known as *k*-tuple methods, are heuristic methods that are not guaranteed to find an optimal alignment solution, but are significantly more efficient than dynamic programming.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] These methods are especially useful in large-scale database searches where it is understood that a large proportion of the candidate sequences will have essentially no significant match with the query sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Word methods are best known for their implementation in the database search tools FASTA and the BLAST family.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Word methods identify a series of short, nonoverlapping subsequences ("words") in the query sequence that are then matched to candidate database sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The relative positions of the word in the two sequences being compared are subtracted to obtain an offset; this will indicate a region of alignment if multiple distinct words produce the same offset.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Only if this region is detected do these methods apply more sensitive alignment criteria; thus, many unnecessary comparisons with sequences of no appreciable similarity are eliminated.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In the FASTA method, the user defines a value *k* to use as the word length with which to search the database.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The method is slower but more sensitive at lower values of *k*, which are also preferred for searches involving a very short query sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The BLAST family of search methods provides a number of algorithms optimized for particular types of queries, such as searching for distantly related sequence matches.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] BLAST was developed to provide a faster alternative to FASTA without sacrificing much accuracy; like FASTA, BLAST uses a word search of length *k*, but evaluates only the most significant word matches, rather than every word match as does FASTA.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Most BLAST implementations use a fixed default word length that is optimized for the query and database type, and that is changed only under special circumstances, such as when searching with repetitive or very short query sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Implementations can be found via a number of web portals, such as EMBL FASTA and NCBI BLAST.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Multiple sequence alignment is an extension of pairwise alignment to incorporate more than two sequences at a time.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Multiple alignment methods try to align all of the sequences in a given query set.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Multiple alignments are often used in identifying conserved sequence regions across a group of sequences hypothesized to be evolutionarily related.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Such conserved sequence motifs can be used in conjunction with structural and mechanistic information to locate the catalytic active sites of enzymes.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Alignments are also used to aid in establishing evolutionary relationships by constructing phylogenetic trees.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Multiple sequence alignments are computationally difficult to produce and most formulations of the problem lead to NP-complete combinatorial optimization problems.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Nevertheless, the utility of these alignments in bioinformatics has led to the development of a variety of methods suitable for aligning three or more sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The technique of dynamic programming is theoretically applicable to any number of sequences; however, because it is computationally expensive in both time and memory, it is rarely used for more than three or four sequences in its most basic form.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] This method requires constructing the *n*-dimensional equivalent of the sequence matrix formed from two sequences, where *n* is the number of sequences in the query.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Standard dynamic programming is first used on all pairs of query sequences and then the "alignment space" is filled in by considering possible matches or gaps at intermediate positions, eventually constructing an alignment essentially between each two-sequence alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Although this technique is computationally expensive, its guarantee of a global optimum solution is useful in cases where only a few sequences need to be aligned accurately.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] One method for reducing the computational demands of dynamic programming, which relies on the "sum of pairs" objective function, has been implemented in the MSA software package.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Progressive, hierarchical, or tree methods generate a multiple sequence alignment by first aligning the most similar sequences and then adding successively less related sequences or groups to the alignment until the entire query set has been incorporated into the solution.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The initial tree describing the sequence relatedness is based on pairwise comparisons that may include heuristic pairwise alignment methods similar to FASTA.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Progressive alignment results are dependent on the choice of "most related" sequences and thus can be sensitive to inaccuracies in the initial pairwise alignments.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Most progressive multiple sequence alignment methods additionally weight the sequences in the query set according to their relatedness, which reduces the likelihood of making a poor choice of initial sequences and thus improves alignment accuracy.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Many variations of the Clustal progressive implementation are used for multiple sequence alignment, phylogenetic tree construction, and as input for protein structure prediction.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] A slower but more accurate variant of the progressive method is known as T-Coffee.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Iterative methods attempt to improve on the heavy dependence on the accuracy of the initial pairwise alignments, which is the weak point of the progressive methods.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Iterative methods optimize an objective function based on a selected alignment scoring method by assigning an initial global alignment and then realigning sequence subsets.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The realigned subsets are then themselves aligned to produce the next iteration's multiple sequence alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Various ways of selecting the sequence subgroups and objective function are reviewed in.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Motif finding, also known as profile analysis, constructs global multiple sequence alignments that attempt to align short conserved sequence motifs among the sequences in the query set.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] This is usually done by first constructing a general global multiple sequence alignment, after which the highly conserved regions are isolated and used to construct a set of profile matrices.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The profile matrix for each conserved region is arranged like a scoring matrix but its frequency counts for each amino acid or nucleotide at each position are derived from the conserved region's character distribution rather than from a more general empirical distribution.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The profile matrices are then used to search other sequences for occurrences of the motif they characterize.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In cases where the original data set contained a small number of sequences, or only highly related sequences, pseudocounts are added to normalize the character distributions represented in the motif.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] A variety of general optimization algorithms commonly used in computer science have also been applied to the multiple sequence alignment problem.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Genetic algorithms and simulated annealing have also been used in optimizing multiple sequence alignment scores as judged by a scoring function like the sum-of-pairs method.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] More complete details and software packages can be found in the main article multiple sequence alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The Burrows–Wheeler transform has been successfully applied to fast short read alignment in popular tools such as Bowtie and BWA.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Structural alignments, which are usually specific to protein and sometimes RNA sequences, use information about the secondary and tertiary structure of the protein or RNA molecule to aid in aligning the sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Because both protein and RNA structure is more evolutionarily conserved than sequence, structural alignments can be more reliable between sequences that are very distantly related and that have diverged so extensively that sequence comparison cannot reliably detect their similarity.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Structural alignments are used as the "gold standard" in evaluating alignments for homology-based protein structure prediction because they explicitly align regions of the protein sequence that are structurally similar rather than relying exclusively on sequence information.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] However, clearly structural alignments cannot be used in structure prediction because at least one sequence in the query set is the target to be modeled, for which the structure is not known.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The DALI method, or distance matrix alignment, is a fragment-based method for constructing structural alignments based on contact similarity patterns between successive hexapeptides in the query sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] It can generate pairwise or multiple alignments and identify a query sequence's structural neighbors in the Protein Data Bank (PDB).
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] It has been used to construct the FSSP structural alignment database (Fold classification based on Structure-Structure alignment of Proteins, or Families of Structurally Similar Proteins).
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] A DALI webserver can be accessed at DALI and the FSSP is located at The Dali Database.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] SSAP (sequential structure alignment program) is a dynamic programming-based method of structural alignment that uses atom-to-atom vectors in structure space as comparison points.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] It has been extended since its original description to include multiple as well as pairwise alignments, and has been used in the construction of the CATH (Class, Architecture, Topology, Homology) hierarchical database classification of protein folds.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The CATH database can be accessed at CATH Protein Structure Classification.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The combinatorial extension method of structural alignment generates a pairwise structural alignment by using local geometry to align short fragments of the two proteins being analyzed and then assembles these fragments into a larger alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] A path from one protein structure state to the other is then traced through the matrix by extending the growing alignment one fragment at a time.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The optimal such path defines the combinatorial-extension alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] A web-based server implementing the method and providing a database of pairwise alignments of structures in the Protein Data Bank is located at the Combinatorial Extension website.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Phylogenetics and sequence alignment are closely related fields due to the shared necessity of evaluating sequence relatedness.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The field of phylogenetics makes extensive use of sequence alignments in the construction and interpretation of phylogenetic trees, which are used to classify the evolutionary relationships between homologous genes represented in the genomes of divergent species.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The degree to which sequences in a query set differ is qualitatively related to the sequences' evolutionary distance from one another.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Roughly speaking, high sequence identity suggests that the sequences in question have a comparatively young most recent common ancestor, while low identity suggests that the divergence is more ancient.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Therefore, it does not account for possible difference among organisms or species in the rates of DNA repair or the possible functional conservation of specific regions in a sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] More statistically accurate methods allow the evolutionary rate on each branch of the phylogenetic tree to vary, thus producing better estimates of coalescence times for genes.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Progressive multiple alignment techniques produce a phylogenetic tree by necessity because they incorporate sequences into the growing alignment in order of relatedness.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Other techniques that assemble multiple sequence alignments and phylogenetic trees score and sort trees first and calculate a multiple sequence alignment from the highest-scoring tree.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Commonly used methods of phylogenetic tree construction are mainly heuristic because the problem of selecting the optimal tree, like the problem of selecting the optimal multiple sequence alignment, is NP-hard.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Sequence alignments are useful in bioinformatics for identifying sequence similarity, producing phylogenetic trees, and developing homology models of protein structures.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] However, the biological relevance of sequence alignments is not always clear.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In database searches such as BLAST, statistical methods can determine the likelihood of a particular alignment between sequences or sequence regions arising by chance given the size and composition of the database being searched.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] These values can vary significantly depending on the search space.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In particular, the likelihood of finding a given alignment by chance increases if the database consists only of sequences from the same organism as the query sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Repetitive sequences in the database or query can also distort both the search results and the assessment of statistical significance; BLAST automatically filters such repetitive sequences in the query to avoid apparent hits that are statistical artifacts.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Methods of statistical significance estimation for gapped sequence alignments are available in the literature.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Statistical significance indicates the probability that an alignment of a given quality could arise by chance, but does not indicate how much superior a given alignment is to alternative alignments of the same sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Measures of alignment credibility indicate the extent to which the best scoring alignments for a given pair of sequences are substantially similar.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Methods of alignment credibility estimation for gapped sequence alignments are available in the literature.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The choice of a scoring function that reflects biological or statistical observations about known sequences is important to producing good alignments.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Protein sequences are frequently aligned using substitution matrices that reflect the probabilities of given character-to-character substitutions.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] A series of matrices called PAM matrices (Point Accepted Mutation matrices, originally defined by Margaret Dayhoff and sometimes referred to as "Dayhoff matrices") explicitly encode evolutionary approximations regarding the rates and probabilities of particular amino acid mutations.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Another common series of scoring matrices, known as BLOSUM (Blocks Substitution Matrix), encodes empirically derived substitution probabilities.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Variants of both types of matrices are used to detect sequences with differing levels of divergence, thus allowing users of BLAST or FASTA to restrict searches to more closely related matches or expand to detect more divergent sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Gap penalties account for the introduction of a gap - on the evolutionary model, an insertion or deletion mutation - in both nucleotide and protein sequences, and therefore the penalty values should be proportional to the expected rate of such mutations.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The quality of the alignments produced therefore depends on the quality of the scoring function.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] It can be very useful and instructive to try the same alignment several times with different choices for scoring matrix and/or gap penalty values and compare the results.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Regions where the solution is weak or non-unique can often be identified by observing which regions of the alignment are robust to variations in alignment parameters.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Sequenced RNA, such as expressed sequence tags and full-length mRNAs, can be aligned to a sequenced genome to find where there are genes and get information about alternative splicing and RNA editing.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Sequence alignment is also a part of genome assembly, where sequences are aligned to find overlap so that *contigs* (long stretches of sequence) can be formed.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Another use is SNP analysis, where sequences from different individuals are aligned to find single basepairs that are often different in a population.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The methods used for biological sequence alignment have also found applications in other fields, most notably in natural language processing and in social sciences, where the Needleman-Wunsch algorithm is usually referred to as Optimal matching.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Techniques that generate the set of elements from which words will be selected in natural-language generation algorithms have borrowed multiple sequence alignment techniques from bioinformatics to produce linguistic versions of computer-generated mathematical proofs.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] In the field of historical and comparative linguistics, sequence alignment has been used to partially automate the comparative method by which linguists traditionally reconstruct languages.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Business and marketing research has also applied multiple sequence alignment techniques in analyzing series of purchases over time.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] A more complete list of available software categorized by algorithm and alignment type is available at sequence alignment software, but common software tools used for general sequence alignment tasks include ClustalW2 and T-coffee for alignment, and BLAST and FASTA3x for database searching.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Commercial tools such as DNASTAR Lasergene, Geneious, and PatternHunter are also available.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Tools annotated as performing sequence alignment are listed in the bio.tools registry.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] Alignment algorithms and software can be directly compared to one another using a standardized set of benchmark reference multiple sequence alignments known as BAliBASE.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The data set consists of structural alignments, which can be considered a standard against which purely sequence-based methods are compared.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] The relative performance of many common alignment methods on frequently encountered alignment problems has been tabulated and selected results published online at BAliBASE.
[src:sequence-alignment/sequence-alignment] A comprehensive list of BAliBASE scores for many (currently 12) different alignment tools can be computed within the protein workbench STRAP.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The **Smith–Waterman algorithm** performs local sequence alignment; that is, for determining similar regions between two strings of nucleic acid sequences or protein sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Instead of looking at the entire sequence, the Smith–Waterman algorithm compares segments of all possible lengths and optimizes the similarity measure.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The algorithm was first proposed by Temple F.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Like the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm, of which it is a variation, Smith–Waterman is a dynamic programming algorithm.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] As such, it has the desirable property that it is guaranteed to find the optimal local alignment with respect to the scoring system being used (which includes the substitution matrix and the gap-scoring scheme).
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The main difference to the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm is that negative scoring matrix cells are set to zero.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Traceback procedure starts at the highest scoring matrix cell and proceeds until a cell with score zero is encountered, yielding the highest scoring local alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Because of its quadratic time complexity, it often cannot be practically applied to large-scale problems and is replaced in favor of computationally more efficient alternatives such as (Gotoh, 1982), (Altschul and Erickson, 1986), and (Myers and Miller, 1988).
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Wunsch proposed a heuristic homology algorithm for sequence alignment, also referred to as the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] It is a global alignment algorithm that requires $O(mn)$ calculation steps ( m and n are the lengths of the two sequences being aligned).
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] It uses the iterative calculation of a matrix for the purpose of showing global alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In the following decade, Sankoff, Reichert, Beyer and others formulated alternative heuristic algorithms for analyzing gene sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Sellers introduced a system for measuring sequence distances.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In 1976, Waterman et al. added the concept of gaps into the original measurement system.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In 1981, Smith and Waterman published their Smith–Waterman algorithm for calculating local alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The Smith–Waterman algorithm is fairly demanding of time: To align two sequences of lengths m and n , $O(m^{2}n+n^{2}m)$ time is required.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Gotoh and Altschul optimized the algorithm to $O(mn)$ steps.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The space complexity was optimized by Myers and Miller from $O(mn)$ to $O(n)$ (linear), where n is the length of the shorter sequence, for the case where only one of the many possible optimal alignments is desired.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Chowdhury, Le, and Ramachandran later optimized the cache performance of the algorithm while keeping the space usage linear in the total length of the input sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In recent years, genome projects conducted on a variety of organisms generated massive amounts of sequence data for genes and proteins, which requires computational analysis.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Sequence alignment shows the relations between genes or between proteins, leading to a better understanding of their homology and functionality.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Sequence alignment can also reveal conserved domains and motifs.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] One motivation for local alignment is the difficulty of obtaining correct alignments in regions of low similarity between distantly related biological sequences, because mutations have added too much 'noise' over evolutionary time to allow for a meaningful comparison of those regions.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Local alignment avoids such regions altogether and focuses on those with a positive score, i.e. those with an evolutionarily conserved signal of similarity.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] A prerequisite for local alignment is a negative expectation score.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The expectation score is defined as the average score that the scoring system (substitution matrix and gap penalties) would yield for a random sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Another motivation for using local alignments is that there is a reliable statistical model (developed by Karlin and Altschul) for optimal local alignments.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The alignment of unrelated sequences tends to produce optimal local alignment scores which follow an extreme value distribution.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] This property allows programs to produce an expectation value for the optimal local alignment of two sequences, which is a measure of how often two unrelated sequences would produce an optimal local alignment whose score is greater than or equal to the observed score.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Very low expectation values indicate that the two sequences in question might be homologous, meaning they might share a common ancestor.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Let $A=a_{1}a_{2}...a_{n}$ and $B=b_{1}b_{2}...b_{m}$ be the sequences to be aligned, where n and m are the lengths of A and B respectively.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Construct a scoring matrix H and initialize its first row and first column.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The size of the scoring matrix is $(n+1)*(m+1)$ .
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Starting at the highest score in the scoring matrix H and ending at a matrix cell that has a score of 0, traceback based on the source of each score recursively to generate the best local alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Smith–Waterman algorithm aligns two sequences by matches/mismatches (also known as substitutions), insertions, and deletions.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Both insertions and deletions are the operations that introduce gaps, which are represented by dashes.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The dimensions of the scoring matrix are 1+length of each sequence respectively.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] All the elements of the first row and the first column are set to 0.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The extra first row and first column make it possible to align one sequence to another at any position, and setting them to 0 makes the terminal gap free from penalty.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Score each element from left to right, top to bottom in the matrix, considering the outcomes of substitutions (diagonal scores) or adding gaps (horizontal and vertical scores).
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] If none of the scores are positive, this element gets a 0.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Otherwise the highest score is used and the source of that score is recorded.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Starting at the element with the highest score, traceback based on the source of each score recursively, until 0 is encountered.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The segments that have the highest similarity score based on the given scoring system is generated in this process.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] To obtain the second best local alignment, apply the traceback process starting at the second highest score outside the trace of the best alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The Smith–Waterman algorithm finds the segments in two sequences that have similarities while the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm aligns two complete sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Therefore, they serve different purposes.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Both algorithms use the concepts of a substitution matrix, a gap penalty function, a scoring matrix, and a traceback process.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] One of the most important distinctions is that no negative score is assigned in the scoring system of the Smith–Waterman algorithm, which enables local alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] When any element has a score lower than zero, it means that the sequences up to this position have no similarities; this element will then be set to zero to eliminate influence from previous alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In this way, calculation can continue to find alignment in any position afterwards.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The initial scoring matrix of Smith–Waterman algorithm enables the alignment of any segment of one sequence to an arbitrary position in the other sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In Needleman–Wunsch algorithm, however, end gap penalty also needs to be considered in order to align the full sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Each base substitution or amino acid substitution is assigned a score.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In general, matches are assigned positive scores, and mismatches are assigned relatively lower scores.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Different base substitutions or amino acid substitutions can have different scores.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The substitution matrix of amino acids is usually more complicated than that of the bases.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Gap penalty designates scores for insertion or deletion.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] A simple gap penalty strategy is to use fixed score for each gap.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In biology, however, the score needs to be counted differently for practical reasons.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] On one hand, partial similarity between two sequences is a common phenomenon; on the other hand, a single gene mutation event can result in insertion of a single long gap.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Therefore, connected gaps forming a long gap usually is more favored than multiple scattered, short gaps.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In order to take this difference into consideration, the concepts of gap opening and gap extension have been added to the scoring system.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The gap opening score is usually higher than the gap extension score.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] For instance, the default parameters in EMBOSS Water are: gap opening = 10, gap extension = 0.5.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Here we discuss two common strategies for gap penalty.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] where $W_{1}$ is the cost of a single gap.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The gap penalty is directly proportional to the gap length.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The simplified algorithm uses $O(mn)$ steps.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] When an element is being scored, only the gap penalties from the elements that are directly adjacent to this element need to be considered.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] where v is the gap opening penalty, and u is the gap extension penalty.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] For example, the penalty for a gap of length 2 is $2u+v$ .
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] An arbitrary gap penalty was used in the original Smith–Waterman algorithm paper.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] It uses $O(m^{2}n)$ steps, therefore is quite demanding of time.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Gotoh optimized the steps for an affine gap penalty to $O(mn)$ , but the optimized algorithm only attempts to find one optimal alignment, and the optimal alignment is not guaranteed to be found.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Altschul modified Gotoh's algorithm to find all optimal alignments while maintaining the computational complexity.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Later, Myers and Miller pointed out that Gotoh and Altschul's algorithm can be further modified based on the method that was published by Hirschberg in 1975, and applied this method.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Myers and Miller's algorithm can align two sequences using $O(n)$ space, with n being the length of the shorter sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Chowdhury, Le, and Ramachandran later showed how to run Gotoh's algorithm cache-efficiently in linear space using a different recursive divide-and-conquer strategy than the one used by Hirschberg.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The resulting algorithm runs faster than Myers and Miller's algorithm in practice due to its superior cache performance.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Take the alignment of sequences TACGGGCCCGCTAC and TAGCCCTATCGGTCA as an example.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] When linear gap penalty function is used, the result is (Alignments performed by EMBOSS Water.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Substitution matrix is DNAfull (similarity score: +5 for matching characters otherwise -4).
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] This example shows that an affine gap penalty can help avoid scattered small gaps.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The function of the scoring matrix is to conduct one-to-one comparisons between all components in two sequences and record the optimal alignment results.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The scoring process reflects the concept of dynamic programming.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The final optimal alignment is found by iteratively expanding the growing optimal alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In other words, the current optimal alignment is generated by deciding which path (match/mismatch or inserting gap) gives the highest score from the previous optimal alignment.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The size of the matrix is the length of one sequence plus 1 by the length of the other sequence plus 1.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The additional first row and first column serve the purpose of aligning one sequence to any positions in the other sequence.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Both the first line and the first column are set to 0 so that end gap is not penalized.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Take the alignment of DNA sequences TGTTACGG and GGTTGACTA as an example.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Initialize and fill the scoring matrix, shown as below.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] This figure shows the scoring process of the first three elements.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The yellow color indicates the bases that are being considered.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The red color indicates the highest possible score for the cell being scored.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The finished scoring matrix is shown below on the left.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] An element can receive score from more than one element, each will form a different path if this element is traced back.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In case of multiple highest scores, traceback should be done starting with each highest score.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The traceback process is shown below on the right.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The best local alignment is generated in the reverse direction.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] An implementation of the Smith–Waterman Algorithm, SSEARCH, is available in the FASTA sequence analysis package from UVA FASTA Downloads.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] This implementation includes Altivec accelerated code for PowerPC G4 and G5 processors that speeds up comparisons 10–20-fold, using a modification of the Wozniak, 1997 approach, and an SSE2 vectorization developed by Farrar making optimal protein sequence database searches quite practical.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] A library, SSW, extends Farrar's implementation to return alignment information in addition to the optimal Smith–Waterman score.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Cray demonstrated acceleration of the Smith–Waterman algorithm using a reconfigurable computing platform based on FPGA chips, with results showing up to 28x speed-up over standard microprocessor-based solutions.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Another FPGA-based version of the Smith–Waterman algorithm shows FPGA (Virtex-4) speedups up to 100x over a 2.2 GHz Opteron processor.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The TimeLogic DeCypher and CodeQuest systems also accelerate Smith–Waterman and Framesearch using PCIe FPGA cards.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] A 2011 Master's thesis includes an analysis of FPGA-based Smith–Waterman acceleration.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In a 2016 publication OpenCL code compiled with Xilinx SDAccel accelerates genome sequencing, beats CPU/GPU performance/W by 12-21x, a very efficient implementation was presented.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Using one PCIe FPGA card equipped with a Xilinx Virtex-7 2000T FPGA, the performance per Watt level was better than CPU/GPU by 12-21x.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] A similar method has already been implemented in the Biofacet software since 1997, with the same speed-up factor.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Several GPU implementations of the algorithm in NVIDIA's CUDA C platform are also available.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] However, the same tests running on dual NVidia GeForce 8800 GTX cards are almost twice as fast as the Farrar implementation for all sequence sizes tested.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] A newer GPU CUDA implementation of SW is now available that is faster than previous versions and also removes limitations on query lengths.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Eleven different SW implementations on CUDA have been reported, three of which report speedups of 30X.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Finally, other GPU-accelerated implementations of the Smith-Waterman can be found in NVIDIA Parabricks, NVIDIA's software suite for genome analysis.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In 2000, a fast implementation of the Smith–Waterman algorithm using the *single instruction, multiple data* (SIMD) technology available in Intel Pentium MMX processors and similar technology was described in a publication by Rognes and Seeberg.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In contrast to the Wozniak (1997) approach, the new implementation was based on vectors parallel with the query sequence, not diagonal vectors.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The company Sencel Bioinformatics has applied for a patent covering this approach.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Sencel is developing the software further and provides executables for academic use free of charge.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] A SSE2 vectorization of the algorithm (Farrar, 2007) is now available providing an 8-16-fold speedup on Intel/AMD processors with SSE2 extensions.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] When running on Intel processor using the Core microarchitecture the SSE2 implementation achieves a 20-fold increase.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Farrar's SSE2 implementation is available as the SSEARCH program in the FASTA sequence comparison package.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The SSEARCH is included in the European Bioinformatics Institute's suite of similarity searching programs.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Danish bioinformatics company CLC bio has achieved speed-ups of close to 200 over standard software implementations with SSE2 on an Intel 2.17 GHz Core 2 Duo CPU, according to a publicly available white paper.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Accelerated version of the Smith–Waterman algorithm, on Intel and Advanced Micro Devices (AMD) based Linux servers, is supported by the GenCore 6 package, offered by Biocceleration.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Performance benchmarks of this software package show up to 10 fold speed acceleration relative to standard software implementation on the same processor.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Currently the only company in bioinformatics to offer both SSE and FPGA solutions accelerating Smith–Waterman, CLC bio has achieved speed-ups of more than 110 over standard software implementations with CLC Bioinformatics Cube.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] The fastest implementation of the algorithm on CPUs with SSSE3 can be found the SWIPE software (Rognes, 2011), which is available under the GNU Affero General Public License.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In parallel, this software compares residues from sixteen different database sequences to one query residue.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] Using a 375 residue query sequence a speed of 106 billion cell updates per second (GCUPS) was achieved on a dual Intel Xeon X5650 six-core processor system, which is over six times more rapid than software based on Farrar's 'striped' approach.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] It is faster than BLAST when using the BLOSUM50 matrix.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] An implementation of Smith–Waterman named *diagonalsw*, in C and C++, uses SIMD instruction sets (SSE4.1 for the x86 platform and AltiVec for the PowerPC platform).
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] It is released under an open-source MIT License.
[src:sequence-alignment/smith-waterman-algorithm] In 2008, Farrar described a port of the Striped Smith–Waterman to the Cell Broadband Engine and reported speeds of 32 and 12 GCUPS on an IBM QS20 blade and a Sony PlayStation 3, respectively.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] In bioinformatics and evolutionary biology, a **substitution matrix** describes the frequency at which a character in a nucleotide sequence or a protein sequence changes to other character states over evolutionary time.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] The information is often in the form of log odds of finding two specific character states aligned and depends on the assumed number of evolutionary changes or sequence dissimilarity between compared sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] It is an application of a stochastic matrix.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Substitution matrices are usually seen in the context of amino acid or DNA sequence alignments, where they are used to calculate similarity scores between the aligned sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] In the process of evolution, from one generation to the next the amino acid sequences of an organism's proteins are gradually altered through the action of DNA mutations.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] over a longer period of evolutionary time.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Each amino acid is more or less likely to mutate into various other amino acids.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] For instance, a hydrophilic residue such as arginine is more likely to be replaced by another hydrophilic residue such as glutamine, than it is to be mutated into a hydrophobic residue such as leucine.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] (Here, a residue refers to an amino acid stripped of a hydrogen and/or a hydroxyl group and inserted in the polymeric chain of a protein.) This is primarily due to redundancy in the genetic code, which translates similar codons into similar amino acids.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Furthermore, mutating an amino acid to a residue with significantly different properties could affect the folding and/or activity of the protein.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] This type of disruptive substitution is likely to be removed from populations by the action of purifying selection because the substitution has a higher likelihood of rendering a protein nonfunctional.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] If we have two amino acid sequences in front of us, we should be able to say something about how likely they are to be derived from a common ancestor, or homologous.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] If we can line up the two sequences using a sequence alignment algorithm such that the mutations required to transform a hypothetical ancestor sequence into both of the current sequences would be evolutionarily plausible, then we'd like to assign a high score to the comparison of the sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] To this end, we will construct a 20x20 matrix where the $(i,j)$ th entry is equal to the probability of the i th amino acid being transformed into the j th amino acid in a certain amount of evolutionary time.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] There are many different ways to construct such a matrix, called a **substitution matrix**.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] The simplest possible substitution matrix would be one in which each amino acid is considered maximally similar to itself, but not able to transform into any other amino acid.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] This identity matrix will succeed in the alignment of very similar amino acid sequences but will be miserable at aligning two distantly related sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] We need to figure out all the probabilities in a more rigorous fashion.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] It turns out that an empirical examination of previously aligned sequences works best.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] We express the probabilities of transformation in what are called log-odds scores.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] where $M_{i,j}$ is the probability that amino acid i transforms into amino acid j , and $p_{i}$ , $p_{j}$ are the frequencies of amino acids *i* and *j*.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] The base of the logarithm is not important, and the same substitution matrix is often expressed in different bases.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] One of the first amino acid substitution matrices, the PAM *(Point Accepted Mutation)* matrix was developed by Margaret Dayhoff in the 1970s.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] This matrix is calculated by observing the differences in closely related proteins.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Because the use of very closely related homologs, the observed mutations are not expected to significantly change the common functions of the proteins.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Thus the observed substitutions (by point mutations) are considered to be accepted by natural selection.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] One PAM unit is defined as 1% of the amino acid positions that have been changed.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] To create a PAM1 substitution matrix, a group of very closely related sequences with mutation frequencies corresponding to one PAM unit is chosen.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Based on collected mutational data from this group of sequences, a substitution matrix can be derived.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] This PAM1 matrix estimates what rate of substitution would be expected if 1% of the amino acids had changed.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] The PAM1 matrix is used as the basis for calculating other matrices by assuming that repeated mutations would follow the same pattern as those in the PAM1 matrix, and multiple substitutions can occur at the same site.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] With this assumption, the PAM2 matrix can estimated by squaring the probabilities.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Using this logic, Dayhoff derived matrices as high as PAM250.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Usually the PAM 30 and the PAM70 are used.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Dayhoff's methodology of comparing closely related species turned out not to work very well for aligning evolutionarily divergent sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Sequence changes over long evolutionary time scales are not well approximated by compounding small changes that occur over short time scales.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] The BLOSUM *(BLOck SUbstitution Matrix)* series of matrices rectifies this problem.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Henikoff & Henikoff constructed these matrices using multiple alignments of evolutionarily divergent proteins.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] The probabilities used in the matrix calculation are computed by looking at "blocks" of conserved sequences found in multiple protein alignments.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] These conserved sequences are assumed to be of functional importance within related proteins and will therefore have lower substitution rates than less conserved regions.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] To reduce bias from closely related sequences on substitution rates, segments in a block with a sequence identity above a certain threshold were clustered, reducing the weight of each such cluster (Henikoff and Henikoff).
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] For the BLOSUM62 matrix, this threshold was set at 62%.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Pairs frequencies were then counted between clusters, hence pairs were only counted between segments less than 62% identical.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] One would use a higher numbered BLOSUM matrix for aligning two closely related sequences and a lower number for more divergent sequences.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] It turns out that the BLOSUM62 matrix does an excellent job detecting similarities in distant sequences, and this is the matrix used by default in most recent alignment applications such as BLAST.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] It also turns out the BLOSUM computer code written by Henikoff and Henikoff does not exactly match the description in their paper.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Surprisingly, this commonly used "wrong" version has better search performance.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] The PAM matrices are based on mutations observed throughout a global alignment, this includes both highly conserved and highly mutable regions.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] The BLOSUM matrices are based only on highly conserved regions in series of alignments forbidden to contain gaps.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] The method used to count the replacements is different: unlike the PAM matrix, the BLOSUM procedure uses groups of sequences within which not all mutations are counted the same.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Higher numbers in the PAM matrix naming scheme denote larger evolutionary distance, while larger numbers in the BLOSUM matrix naming scheme denote higher sequence similarity and therefore smaller evolutionary distance.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Example: PAM150 is used for more distant sequences than PAM100; BLOSUM62 is used for closer sequences than BLOSUM50.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] A number of newer substitution matrices have been proposed to deal with inadequacies in earlier designs.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] For a list of more models (including irreversible i.e. asymmetric and/or specialized ones), see the documentation for recent bioinformatic software including IQ-Tree, PhyML, and RAxML.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] The real substitution rates in a protein depends not only on the identity of the amino acid, but also on the specific structural or sequence context it is in.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Many specialized matrices have been developed for these contexts, such as in transmembrane alpha helices, for combinations of secondary structure states and solvent accessibility states, or for local sequence-structure contexts.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] These context-specific substitution matrices lead to generally improved alignment quality at some cost of speed but are not yet widely used.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Since the 2000s, an increasing amount of matrices are defined for subsets of proteins not optimally aligned by traditional "general-purpose" matrices.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Recently, sequence context-specific amino acid similarities have been derived that do not need substitution matrices but that rely on a library of sequence contexts instead.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Using this idea, a context-specific extension of the popular BLAST program has been demonstrated to achieve a twofold sensitivity improvement for remotely related sequences over BLAST at similar speeds (CS-BLAST).
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] With nucleotides only having four possible values (in most bioinformatic sequences), the emphasis lies not in setting fixed values in the matrix, but in designing parameterized models that fit the observed evolution of the input sequence as it's being aligned.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Although "transition matrix" is often used interchangeably with "substitution matrix" in fields other than bioinformatics, the former term is problematic in bioinformatics.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] With regards to nucleotide substitutions, "transition" is also used to indicate those substitutions that are between the two-ring purines (A → G and G → A) or are between the one-ring pyrimidines (C → T and T → C).
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] Because these substitutions do not require a change in the number of rings, they occur more frequently than the other substitutions.
[src:sequence-alignment/substitution-matrix] "Transversion" is the term used to indicate the slower-rate substitutions that change a purine to a pyrimidine or vice versa (A ↔ C, A ↔ T, G ↔ C, and G ↔ T).
